td> </tr> </table> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A classic way to trade bond=
s is that you call up a broker-dealer (generally a trader at a big bank) an=
d say =E2=80=9CI want to buy Bond X and I=E2=80=99ll pay up to 90 cents on =
the dollar for it,=E2=80=9D and then the dealer thinks about who else she k=
nows who owns Bond X and might want to sell it, and she thinks =E2=80=9Cah =
yes Customer Y was telling me the other day that she wants to get rid of Bo=
nd X,=E2=80=9D so she calls Customer Y and says =E2=80=9Chey do you want to=
 sell Bond X,=E2=80=9D and the Customer Y says =E2=80=9Csure but I won=E2=
=80=99t sell for less than 91 cents on the dollar,=E2=80=9D and then the de=
aler tries to negotiate you up and/or negotiate Customer Y down so that a t=
rade can happen. If she gets you up to 90.5, and gets Customer Y down to 90=
.25, then a trade will happen: The dealer will buy from Customer Y at 90.2=
5 and sell to you at 90.5, collecting 0.25 as payment for her work.</p> <p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not the only way for bond trades to happe=
n =E2=80=94 a lot of trading is electronic, and sometimes the dealer will o=
wn Bond X herself, and just sell to you out of inventory =E2=80=94=C2=A0but=
 it is a common one. It is often called a =E2=80=9Criskless principal=E2=80=
=9D trade: The dealer buys from Customer Y for her own account, and then se=
lls to you at a markup, but she does both trades at the same time without t=
aking any market risk by holding the bonds.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">There is no magic to these numbers, 90 and 91 or whatever. It=E2=80=99s s=
ort of natural for the best bid for a bond (the highest price you, or anyon=
e, will pay for it) to be=C2=A0lower than the best offer for that bond (the=
 lowest price Customer Y, or anyone, will accept to sell it), so it takes s=
ome effort or new information to make trades happen. Your model could be =
=E2=80=9Cthere is a market price, say 90.5, and any trades that would have =
happened at the market price have already happened, so anybody currently ho=
lding the bond wants more than 90.5, and anyone looking for the bond wants =
to pay less than 90.5=E2=80=9D (This is a roughly plausible model of the st=
ock market, for instance.)</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not alway=
s true in bond markets, though, because some bonds don=E2=80=99t trade that=
 often or have much in the way of a public =E2=80=9Cmarket price.=E2=80=9D =
Many bonds =E2=80=94=C2=A0like stocks =E2=80=94=C2=A0trade electronically a=
nd frequently in markets whose prices are pretty widely visible to investor=
s, so you (and Customer Y) might know exactly what the market prices are, b=
ut many don=E2=80=99t. Many trade infrequently and don=E2=80=99t have bid a=
nd offer prices displayed on any electronic platform. You might not know ho=
w much Bond X=C2=A0<em>should=C2=A0</em>cost, and Customer Y might not know=
 how much he should ask for it. So you might call your dealer and say =E2=
=80=9CI want to buy Bond X and I=E2=80=99ll pay up to =E2=80=A6=C2=A095 cen=
ts=3F=E2=80=9D And the dealer might call Customer Y, who might say =E2=80=
=9Csure but I won=E2=80=99t sell for less than 88 cents.=E2=80=9D And then =
there is definitely a trade!</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What is the t=
rade, though=3F If the dealer is acting as a fiduciary for you, she will bu=
y the bond from Customer Y at 88 cents on the dollar and turn around and se=
ll it to you at, say, 88.25, taking a markup of 0.25 for herself. =E2=80=9C=
Good news,=E2=80=9D she will tell you, =E2=80=9CI got you a better price th=
an you asked for.=E2=80=9D On the other hand, if she is acting as a fiducia=
ry for Customer Y, she will tell him =E2=80=9Coh I can do better than 88, I=
=E2=80=99ll buy from you at 94.75,=E2=80=9D and then sell to you at 95, tak=
ing 0.25 for herself. If she values you both equally, she=E2=80=99ll meet i=
n the middle, buying from Customer Y at, say, 91.5 and selling to you at 91=
.75.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or, you know. Or Customer Y will say=
 =E2=80=9Csure but I won=E2=80=99t sell for less than 88 cents,=E2=80=9D an=
d the dealer will say =E2=80=9Cman you are driving a hard bargain, my kids =
need to eat, but okay, fine, I think I can do=C2=A088,=E2=80=9D and then sh=
e will call you and say =E2=80=9Cgood news, it wasn=E2=80=99t easy, but wit=
h hard work and my excellent relationships I was able to get those bonds fo=
r you, here they are, 95 cents on the dollar just like you asked.=E2=80=9D =
And she gets 7 points for herself and a round of applause from her trading =
desk.</p> <p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general your bond dealer, in a ri=
skless principal trade,=C2=A0<em>isn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>a fiduciary for yo=
u, and=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>kind of in the business of making as much mone=
y as she can on her trades, so she might be inclined to take the 7 points. =
But there are important constraints. Here are three:</p> <ol style=3D"list-=
style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">You are, in this hypothetical situation, probably a profe=
ssional investor, an asset manager. (The retail market is works differently=
.) You know all this stuff. You can just ask! The dealer will call you and=
 say =E2=80=9CI found those bonds for you=E2=80=9D and you can say =E2=80=
=9Cwell how much are you paying for them=E2=80=9D and she will probably tel=
l you the truth. She will tell you the truth because she wants to do repeat=
 business with you and cares about her reputation for honesty, because she =
expects you=E2=80=99ll find out if she=E2=80=99s lying, and because, if she=
